		<!-- message -->
		<div>How can one kill that which has no life? <br />
<br />
How can one suspend or revoke a privelage that one does not have? Constitutional rights under the United States constitution apply only to US citizens. People with no citizenship to any country who wage barbaric terrorism against the US should most certainly NOT be given rights and privelages granted to us under the US constitution as citizens of the United States. <br />
<br />
Even in 2004 when the supreme court heard the Rasul case (which by the way is the first time the supreme court has EVER heard a case by an enemy combatant) they most certainly did not grant the unlawful alien combatants the rights and privelages of the United States constitution. <br />
<br />
This act has not limited detainees to petition under article 3 of the geneva conventions to question their detainment, however under the geneva conventions the scope of the treaty is limited to sovereign states within the treaty and their citizens, not individuals without citizenship. Nowhere does it say that there can and should be judicial review of individual detainees. It is the sole responsibility of the state who's citizen is being held to petition the US State department for release which we *have* done when a sovereign state has made the request on behalf of it's citizens. Most of the time they are repatriated and go on to rejoin the jihad.<br />
<br />
Now, we've established that since 1949 (the year of the geneva conventions) the detainees (the alien unlawful combatants) have some rights under the geneva conventions and they have and still are being followed, but absolutely NONE under the US Constitution. However in 2005 congress passed the Detainee Treatment Act which allows the detainees to petition the US military to challenge his/her detention. If the tribunal ascertains that the detainee is being properly held, he or she can appeal to the US Court of appeals in washington DC and if they uphold the detainment then the combatant can petition the supreme court... HOLY CRAP! We've given unlawful alien combatants access to our countrie's civilian court system!<br />
<br />
So basically congress could have simply amended the current laws to specifically exclude terrorists from any rights to Habeas and our court system, which is precicely how the law has been for the last 200 years. Instead they went the other way and actually gave them, in est, access to a form of habeas corpus.<br />
<br />
Now... the DTA was unclear as to whether or not the terrorists already being held, and who had filed petitions to the US courts were protected. The Military commission act now strengthens the DTA by putting a date (9/11/01) and a definition ((i) a person who has engaged in hostilities or who has purposefully and materially supported hostilities against the United States or its co-belligerents who is not a lawful enemy combatant (including a person who is part of the Taliban, al Qaeda, or associated forces); or`(ii) a person who, before, on, or after the date of the enactment of the Military Commissions Act of 2006, has been determined to be an unlawful enemy combatant by a Combatant Status Review Tribunal or another competent tribunal established under the authority of the President or the Secretary of Defense.) to the current terrorist detainees. <br />
<br />
The DTA doesn't specifically name the privelage "habeas corpus" but isn't it the pages inside the book that count, not the cover? The DTA gives the terrorists the same thing as habeas. For the military commission act to give it again would have been redundant.<br />
<br />
For the reasoning of why it would not state this redundant fact... look at it this way. In the US courts for a US citizen, he or she can not re-petition the validity of his or her imprisonment with the same claims they have already made. why the HELL would we allow non-US citizens to do that under the MCA? It doesn't make sense.<br />
<br />
So now we have a situation where terrorists have MORE rights than they have had in the last 200+ years of our country's history, and more than the geneva conventions have given them in 1949 and MORE than an honorable, lawful combatant of a country in which we have officially declared war upon. <br />
<br />
Now tell me (if you've read this far) does it really make you feel better knowing that we've given rights to terrorists that commit mass murder against innocent civilians that lawful combatants (soldiers of another country) that we are officially at war with do not get?!<br />
<br />
I'm sorry, idiots like Olbermann make me sad.<br />
<br />
SO... I have read the MCA (thanks for the heads up Valcor!) and let me cut and paste some points of interest: My comments are in RED<br />
<br />
<b>Sec. 948c</b><br />
<br />
<br />
Any alien unlawful enemy combatant is subject to trial by military commission under this chapter. <font color="Red">And under the DTA they can appeal this to the US courts, just like habeas corpus.<br />
<br />
</font><b>Sec. 949h. Former jeopardy</b><br />
<br />
<b>`(a) In General- No person may, without his consent, be tried by a military commission under this chapter a second time for the same offense.</b><br />
<br />
<b>`(b) Scope of Trial- No proceeding in which the accused has been found guilty by military commission under this chapter upon any charge or specification is a trial in the sense of this section until the finding of guilty has become final after review of the case has been fully completed.</b><br />
<br />
<font color="Red">So the MCA has given terrorists more rights granted to US citizens under the constitution, but not under any previous law, treaty or act.<br />
<br />
<font color="Black">Maybe cutting and pasting isn't the right thing to do... it would make this post go on forever...<br />
<br />
Suffice it to say if you actually head on over to the Library of Congress website and read the MCA, then go and read the DTA... you'll see that Mr. Olbermann has completely distorted the facts and is truly the one trying to deceive you.<br />
<br />
Thank you for your time.<br />
</font></font><br /><br />
<br />
